tive season in the top flight of [[Football in Italy|Italian football]].\n\n== Season overview==\nAfter a disappointing previous season, [[Massimo Moratti]] chose former [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] coach [[H\u00e9ctor C\u00faper]] as the coach of rebirth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2001/maggio/25/Cuper_Inter_non_torna_indietro_ga_0_0105256774.shtml|title=Cuper Inter, non si torna indietro|author1=Luca Curino|author2=Mirko Graziano|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|date=25 May 2001|language=italian}}</ref> C\u00faper managed to line-up a new team, buying players such as [[Francesco Toldo|Toldo]], [[Marco Materazzi|Materazzi]], [[Mohamed Kallon|Kallon]] and [[Nicola Ventola|Ventola]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2001/06/17/anno-orribile-del-calcio-cuper-terim.html|title=L' anno orribile del calcio Cuper e Terim per dimenticare il 2001|author=Luca Bolognini|newspaper=[[la Repubblica]]|date=17 June 2001|page=15|language=italian}}</ref> Inter had a sprint-start, topping the [[2001\u201302 Serie A|league]] and passing several challenges in [[2001\u201302 UEFA Cup|Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/torinointer/torinointer/torinointer.html|title=Kallon sprints Inter nerazzurri at top|website=repubblica.it|date=23 September 2001|language=italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_coppe/brasovinter/brasovinter/brasovinter.html|title=All easy for Inter but Ronaldo stops agains|website=repubblica.it|date=27 September 2001|language=italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_numeri/cinque/cinque/cinque.html|title=Inter top at day 5 It ended fourth|website=repubblica.it|date=1 October 2001|language=italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2001/10/22/milan-gol-in-minuti-sheva-il-re.html|title=Milan, 3 gol in 5 minuti: Sheva \u00e8 il re|author=Gianni Piva|newspaper=la Repubblica|date=22 October 2001|page=35|language=italian}}</ref> 2001 closed with Giuseppe Prisco's death, vicechairman since 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2001/12/14/prisco-un-addio-da-alpino.html|title=Prisco, un addio da alpino|author=Luca Fazzo|newspaper=la Repubblica|date=14 December 2001|page=5|language=italian}}</ref>\n\nIn the second part of season, Inter showed signs of exhaustion: 1\u20132 home loss to [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/interatalanta/interatalanta/interatalanta.html|title=Atalanta beats Inter Title rush still open|website=repubblica.it|date=7 April 2002|language=italian}}</ref> was followed, on Thursday, from European elimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_coppe/feyenoordinter/feyenoordinter/feyenoordinter.html|title=Inter, useless comeback Feyenoord in final|website=repubblica.it|date=11 April 2002|language=italian}}</ref> Before the last league game, against [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], Inter was still at the top with one point over [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and two over [[A.S. Roma|Roma]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2002/05/05/veleni-paure-inter-sogna-lo-scudetto.html|title=Veleni e paure, l'Inter sogna lo scudetto|author=Gianni Mura|newspaper=la Repubblica|date=5 May 2002|page=1|language=italian}}</ref> In the first half, Inter scored twice, but both goals were equalized by Lazio's [[Karel Poborsky|Poborsky]].<ref name=Olimpico>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2002/maggio/06/Inter_paga_grande_illusione_ga_0_0205061470.shtml|title=L' Inter paga la grande illusione|author=Lodovico Maradei|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|date=6 May 2002|language=italian}}</ref> During second half of the match, Lazio - still in race for a [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] spot - scored another two goals, eventually winning the match.<ref name=Olimpico/> Inter fell to third place,<ref name=Olimpico/> enough to qualify for next season's [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] playoff.<ref name=Olimpico/> Lazio-Inter also marked [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]'s last appearance with Inter.<ref name=Olimpico/>\n\n==First-team squad==\n:''Squad at end of season''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/italy/2001-2002/seriea/inter.htm | title=Internazionale (2001-2002) | publisher=Football Squads | accessdate=15 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\n{{Football squad start}}\n{{Football squad player|no=1|nat=ITA|name=[[Francesco Toldo]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Football squad player|no=2|nat=COL|name=[[Iv\u00e1n C\u00f3rdoba]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=3|nat=SLE|name=[[Mohamed Kallon]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Football squad player|no=4|nat=ARG|name=[[Javier Zanetti]]|pos=DF|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Football squad player|no=5|nat=ITA|name=[[Pasquale Padalino]]|pos=DF|other=on loan from [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]}}\n{{Football squad player|no=6|nat=ITA|name=[[Cristiano Zanetti]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=7|nat=POR|name=[[S\u00e9rgio Con\u00e7eic\u00e3o]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=8|nat=ESP|name=[[Francisco Farin\u00f3s]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=9|nat=BRA|name=[[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Football squad player|no=10|nat=NED|name=[[Clarence Seedorf]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=11|nat=ARG|name=[[Andr\u00e9s Guglielminpietro|Guly]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=12|nat=ITA|name=[[Alberto Fontana (footballer, born 1967)|Alberto Fontana]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Football squad player|no=13|nat=CRO|name=[[Dario \u0160imi\u0107]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=14|nat=ITA|name=[[Luigi Di Biagio]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=15|nat=ITA|name=[[Salvatore Ferraro]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Football squad mid}}\n{{Football squad player|no=16|nat=URU|name=[[Gonzalo Sorondo]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Football squad player|no=17|