{"title_page": "Delta Phi", "text_new": "{{redirect|St. Elmo Hall||St. Elmo (disambiguation)|and|San Telmo (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date = June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Fraternity |\n| letters = \u0394\u03a6\n| name = Delta Phi (St. Elmo Hall)\n| nickname = St. Elmo Club / St. Elmo Hall\n| motto = \"Semper Ubique\"\n| crest = [[Image:Deltaphi3.jpg|175px]]\n| founded = {{start date and years ago|1827|11|17}}\n| type = Social\n| scope = National\n| address = P.O. Box 4633\n| city = Chapel Hill\n| state = North Carolina\n| country = USA\n| chapters = 13 active chapters\n| homepage = [http://www.deltaphifraternity.org deltaphifraternity.org]\n| colors = Columbia Blue and White\n| free_label =\n\n| free =\n\n| birthplace = [[Union College]]\n| flower =\n| symbol = The [[Maltese Cross]]\n| patron saint = [[Erasmus of Formia|St. Elmo]]\n}}\n\n'''Delta Phi''' ('''\u0394\u03a6''') is a [[fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] founded in 1827 at [[Union College]] in [[Schenectady, New York]]. Along with the [[Kappa Alpha Society]] and [[Sigma Phi|Sigma Phi Society]], Delta Phi was the third and last member of the [[Union Triad]].\n\n==History==\nDelta Phi and the other fraternities of the Union Triad were established during a time of strong anti-[[Freemasonry|Masonic]] sentiment in the United States. Because fraternities were [[secret societies]] at the time, they also became targets of the anti-Masonic movement. This led [[Phi Beta Kappa]], the original fraternity, to abandon secrecy and become an honor society.\n\nIn the early 1830s, Dr. [[Eliphalet Nott]], president of Union College, called for the dissolution of all fraternities. Before this policy could be enacted, John Jay Hyde, a member of Delta Phi, argued the benefits of the fraternity system so convincingly that Nott relented and permitted the organizations to remain in existence. Hyde went on to design the badge still worn by members of Delta Phi, which includes a [[Maltese Cross]], a symbol used by the [[Knights Hospitaller|Knights of Malta]].\n\nThis connection to the Knights of Malta led Delta Phi to become known as \"The St. Elmo Club\", a name first used by the [[Omicron]] chapter at [[Yale University]], which since has transformed into a senior secret society known as [[St. Elmo (secret society)|St. Elmo Society]]. The brothers there used the name of [[Erasmus of Formiae|St. Elmo]], the patron saint of mariners and the Knights of Malta. Some of Delta Phi's chapter houses are also known as \"St. Elmo Hall\".\n\n===Delta Phi today===\n[[Image:Delta Phi Badge.jpg|left]]Delta Phi remains a small fraternity with thirteen active chapters and few chapters with more than several dozen members. It has resisted expansion in order to create an \"intimate, personal experience\"<ref name=\"deltaphi1\">[http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/chapters.cfm Delta Phi Fraternity]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08Q7DSy?url=http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/chapters.cfm |date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> for its members. The fraternity's current expansion policy is to reactivate dormant chapters.<ref name=\"deltaphi1\"/>  As a member of the [[Union Triad]], Delta Phi is the third oldest fraternity in the United States.\n\n==Governance and organization==\nOwing mostly to its development in the early 19th century, Delta Phi organizes itself federally. Individual alumni chapters still exercise significant power over chapter governance. Those powers that are given in the national organization are vested in the Board of Governors.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/administ.html Delta Phi Fraternity]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08QZfiV?url=http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/administ.html |date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> The board consists of one member appointed from each alumni chapter plus two undergraduate representatives elected at the annual leadership conference the fraternity sponsors.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Among the duties given to the board is hiring the Executive Director who oversees day-to-day management of the fraternity.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn addition to the national governing organization of the fraternity, Delta Phi alumni have also established the Saint Elmo Foundation which, among other things, sponsors the annual leadership weekend and provides scholarships to undergraduate members of Delta Phi.<ref>http://www.st-elmo.net/foundation/ {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050208043459/http://www.st-elmo.net/foundation/ |date=February 8, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni membership==\n\nOverall alumni participation among active chapters remains strong, with chapters hosting several social events throughout the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wm.edu/so/deltaphi/alumni.winecheese.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-06-10 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08Rl2O1?url=http://www.wm.edu/so/deltaphi/alumni.winecheese.php |archivedate=December 15, 2010 |df= }}</ref><ref>[http://www.llenroc.org/calendar.asp Delta Phi at Cornell&nbsp;-&nbsp;Calendar of Events]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08SB44R?url=http://www.llenroc.org/calendar.asp |date=December 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn or around November 17 of every year, the national organization sponsors the Founder's Day Dinner at the Saint Elmo Club where undergraduates and alumni celebrate the founding of the fraternity.<ref>[http://www.deltaphi.org/events/ Delta Phi Fraternity]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08TT9zt?url=http://www.deltaphi.org/events/ |date=December 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Founders==\n* Benjamin Burroughs, [[Presbyterian]] [[Minister of religion|minister]] from [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] \n* William Hun Fondey, [[Lawyer|attorney]] from [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* Samuel Lewis Lamberson, Presbyterian [[Minister of religion|minister]] from [[Jamaica, New York|Jamaica]], New York\n* Samuel C. Lawrison, [[United States Navy]] [[surgery|surgeon]] from [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]], [[Florida]]\n* David Hervey Little, [[New York Supreme Court]] [[Justice]] from [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], New York\n* John Mason, [[clergyman]] from Jamaica, New York\n* Joseph Griffiths Masten, [[Mayor]] of [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] from [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], New York\n* Thomas Clark McLaury, [[clergyman]] from [[Lisbon, New York|Lisbon]], New York\n* William Wilson, [[President (education)|President]] of the College of Cincinnati from [[Ireland]]\n\n==Chapters==\n{{overly detailed|section=yes|date=December 2011}}\n\n===Active chapters===\nThere are 12 active chapters of Delta Phi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Active Chapters - Delta Phi Fraternity|url=http://www.deltaphifraternity.org/?page=AChapters}}</ref> \n* Beta - [[Brown University]], Providence, Rhode Island, 1830-2011<sup>[*]</sup>\n* Epsilon - [[Rutgers University]], New Brunswick, New Jersey, 1845<ref>[http://www.deltaphirutgers.org Epsilon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009090546/http://www.deltaphirutgers.org/ |date=2008-10-09}}</ref>\n* Eta - [[University of Pennsylvania]], Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, 1849<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://stelmopenn.2stayconnected.com/ |title=Eta |access-date=2019-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526225847/https://stelmopenn.2stayconnected.com/ |archive-date=2016-05-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Lambda - [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]], Troy, New York, 1864<ref>[http://deltaphirpi.com/ Lambda]</ref>\n* Xi - [[Johns Hopkins University]], Baltimore, Maryland, 1885\n* Pi - [[Cornell University]], Ithaca, New York, 1891<ref>[http://www.llenroc.org/ Pi]</ref>\n* Rho - [[University of Virginia]], Charlottesville, Virginia, 1908\n* Phi - [[Kenyon College]], Gambier, Ohio, 1940\n* Chi - [[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]], Clinton, New York, 1950<ref>[http://students.hamilton.edu/deltaphi/home/ Chi]</ref>\n* Psi - [[Pennsylvania State University]], State College, Pennsylvania, 1960\u20132007, 2015\n* Omega - [[University of Pittsburgh]], Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, 1968<ref>[https://pittdeltaphi.com Omega]</ref>\n* Omega Alpha - [[College of William and Mary]], Williamsburg, Virginia, 1987<ref>[http://wmdeltaphi.wixsite.com/elmo]</ref>\n\n[*] An active fraternity that is no longer affiliated with the national organization\n\n===Inactive chapters===\nThere are 15 inactive chapters of Delta Phi, including the Alpha Chapter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inactive Chapters - Delta Phi Fraternity|url=http://www.deltaphifraternity.org/?page=IAChapters}}</ref> \n* Alpha - [[Union College]], Schenectady, New York, 1827\u20131999\n* Gamma - [[New York University]], New York, New York, 1841\u20132019\n* Delta - [[Columbia University]], New York, New York, 1842\u20132001\n* Zeta - [[Harvard University]], Cambridge, Massachusetts, 1845\u20131901\n* Theta - [[Princeton University]], Princeton, New Jersey, 1854\u20131877\n* Iota - [[University of Michigan]], Ann Arbor, Michigan, 1855\u20131936\n* Kappa - [[University of North Carolina]], Chapel Hill, North Carolina, 1855\u20131861\n* Mu - [[Colgate University]], Hamilton, New York, 1874\u20131876\n* Nu - [[Lehigh University]], Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, 1884-2015<ref>\n* Omicron - [[Yale University]], New Haven, Connecticut, 1889\u20131925[*]\n* Sigma - [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]], Hartford, Connecticut, 1917\u20132001\n* Tau - [[University of Illinois]], Champaign, Illinois, 1920-2009\n* Upsilon - [[Williams College]], Williamstown, Massachusetts, 1926\u20131965\n* Omega Beta - [[Wabash College]], Crawfordsville, Indiana, 1994\u20132001\n[http://web.me.com/deltaphinuchapter/Site/Welcome.html Nu]</ref>\n\n[*] Omicron Chapter dissociated with Delta Phi and is now known as the [[St. Elmo (secret society)|St. Elmo Society]] at Yale.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2011}}\n* [[George Low]] - \u039b - [[NASA]] administrator and 14th President of [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]]\n* [[Garret A. Hobart]] - E - [[Vice President of the United States]] under William McKinley\n* [[George C. Ludlow]]  - E - [[Governor of New Jersey]]\n* [[Paolo Montalb\u00e1n]] - E - actor of stage and screen\n* [[George H. Sharpe|Maj. Gen. George Henry Sharpe]] - E - Civil War spymaster\n* [[Howard Crosby (minister)|Howard Crosby]] - \u0393 - preacher; Chancellor of NYU  \n* [[Edgar Fawcett]] (1847\u20131904) - \u0394 - novelist and poet<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cxATAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA29&lpg=RA1-PA29&dq=delta+hii%7CThe&hl=en#v=onepage&q=delta%20hii%7CThe&f=false |title=The Undergraduate Record: Columbia College. A Book of Statistical Information|year = 1881 |accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Harper & Brothers|The Harper Brothers]] - \u0394 - founders of Harper & Brothers publishing group\n* [[John Pierpont Morgan, Jr.]] - \u0396 - financier; founder of JP Morgan Bank and Morgan Stanley\n* [[John Jacob Astor IV]] - \u0396 - industrialist and philanthropist\n* [[James Roosevelt]] - \u0396 - General, congressman; son of Franklin D. Roosevelt\n* [[Halsey Minor]] - \u03a1 - co-founder and former CEO of [[CNET]] Inc.\n* [[Marvin Bush]] - \u03a1 - [[George W. Bush]]'s younger brother\n* [[Thomas B. Evans, Jr.]] - P - US Congressman\n* [[Stanley Forman Reed]] - \u03a1 - [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n* [[Charles Scribner's Sons|Charles Scribner]] - \u0398 - founder of Charles Scribner's Sons publishing group\n* [[Russell Wayne Baker]] - \u039e - [[Pulitzer Prize]]\u2013winning writer; former host of PBS show ''[[Masterpiece Theatre]]''\n* [[Sullivan Ballou]] - B - author of famous Civil War love letter at the [[First Battle of Bull Run]]\n* [[Finn Wentworth]] N - businessman; COO and owner of New York Yankees; founder of YES Network; philanthropist\n* [[George Santayana]] - Z - Spanish author and philosopher famous for noting that \"those who cannot remember the past, are condemned to repeat it\"\n* [[George Will]] - \u03a3 - Pulitzer Prize-winning conservative newspaper columnist, journalist, and author\n* [[George Macready]] - B - actor\n* [[William P. Carey]] - H - founder of [[W. P. Carey & Co.]]; established the [[Carey Business School]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]], the Carey School of Law at the [[University of Maryland School of Law]], and the [[W. P. Carey School of Business]] at [[Arizona State University]]\n* [[Jay Jones (politician)]] - OA - Delegate for the 89th District of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] <ref>http://www.jayjones.vote/about-delegate-jay-jones</ref><ref>http://wmdeltaphi.wixsite.com/elmo/contact</ref>\n* [[John C. Bauerschmidt]] - \u03a6 - Bishop of Middle Tennessee\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.deltaphi.org/ National Website]\n* [https://archive.is/20071225122953/http://www.dailytargum.com/news/2005/10/27/PageOne/Fraternity.Structure.Began.More.Than.A.Century.Ago-1035924.shtml History of Epsilon] (Daily Targum, 10/2005)\n\n{{Fraternities and Sororities |collapsed}}\n{{North American Interfraternity Conference}}\n\n[[Category:Student organizations established in 1827]]\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:North American Interfraternity Conference]]\n[[Category:Union College (New York)]]\n[[Category:Delta Phi| ]]\n[[Category:1827 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|St. Elmo Hall||St. Elmo (disambiguation)|and|San Telmo (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date = June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Fraternity |\n| letters = \u0394\u03a6\n| name = Delta Phi (St. Elmo Hall)\n| nickname = St. Elmo Club / St. Elmo Hall\n| motto = \"Semper Ubique\"\n| crest = [[Image:Deltaphi3.jpg|175px]]\n| founded = {{start date and years ago|1827|11|17}}\n| type = Social\n| scope = National\n| address = P.O. Box 4633\n| city = Chapel Hill\n| state = North Carolina\n| country = USA\n| chapters = 13 active chapters\n| homepage = [http://www.deltaphifraternity.org deltaphifraternity.org]\n| colors = Columbia Blue and White\n| free_label =\n\n| free =\n\n| birthplace = [[Union College]]\n| flower =\n| symbol = The [[Maltese Cross]]\n| patron saint = [[Erasmus of Formia|St. Elmo]]\n}}\n\n'''Delta Phi''' ('''\u0394\u03a6''') is a [[fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] founded in 1827 at [[Union College]] in [[Schenectady, New York]]. Along with the [[Kappa Alpha Society]] and [[Sigma Phi|Sigma Phi Society]], Delta Phi was the third and last member of the [[Union Triad]].\n\n==History==\nDelta Phi and the other fraternities of the Union Triad were established during a time of strong anti-[[Freemasonry|Masonic]] sentiment in the United States. Because fraternities were [[secret societies]] at the time, they also became targets of the anti-Masonic movement. This led [[Phi Beta Kappa]], the original fraternity, to abandon secrecy and become an honor society.\n\nIn the early 1830s, Dr. [[Eliphalet Nott]], president of Union College, called for the dissolution of all fraternities. Before this policy could be enacted, John Jay Hyde, a member of Delta Phi, argued the benefits of the fraternity system so convincingly that Nott relented and permitted the organizations to remain in existence. Hyde went on to design the badge still worn by members of Delta Phi, which includes a [[Maltese Cross]], a symbol used by the [[Knights Hospitaller|Knights of Malta]].\n\nThis connection to the Knights of Malta led Delta Phi to become known as \"The St. Elmo Club\", a name first used by the [[Omicron]] chapter at [[Yale University]], which since has transformed into a senior secret society known as [[St. Elmo (secret society)|St. Elmo Society]]. The brothers there used the name of [[Erasmus of Formiae|St. Elmo]], the patron saint of mariners and the Knights of Malta. Some of Delta Phi's chapter houses are also known as \"St. Elmo Hall\".\n\n===Delta Phi today===\n[[Image:Delta Phi Badge.jpg|left]]Delta Phi remains a small fraternity with thirteen active chapters and few chapters with more than several dozen members. It has resisted expansion in order to create an \"intimate, personal experience\"<ref name=\"deltaphi1\">[http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/chapters.cfm Delta Phi Fraternity]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08Q7DSy?url=http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/chapters.cfm |date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> for its members. The fraternity's current expansion policy is to reactivate dormant chapters.<ref name=\"deltaphi1\"/>  As a member of the [[Union Triad]], Delta Phi is the third oldest fraternity in the United States.\n\n==Governance and organization==\nOwing mostly to its development in the early 19th century, Delta Phi organizes itself federally. Individual alumni chapters still exercise significant power over chapter governance. Those powers that are given in the national organization are vested in the Board of Governors.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/administ.html Delta Phi Fraternity]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08QZfiV?url=http://www.deltaphi.org/doc/administ.html |date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> The board consists of one member appointed from each alumni chapter plus two undergraduate representatives elected at the annual leadership conference the fraternity sponsors.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Among the duties given to the board is hiring the Executive Director who oversees day-to-day management of the fraternity.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn addition to the national governing organization of the fraternity, Delta Phi alumni have also established the Saint Elmo Foundation which, among other things, sponsors the annual leadership weekend and provides scholarships to undergraduate members of Delta Phi.<ref>http://www.st-elmo.net/foundation/ {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050208043459/http://www.st-elmo.net/foundation/ |date=February 8, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni membership==\n\nOverall alumni participation among active chapters remains strong, with chapters hosting several social events throughout the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wm.edu/so/deltaphi/alumni.winecheese.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-06-10 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08Rl2O1?url=http://www.wm.edu/so/deltaphi/alumni.winecheese.php |archivedate=December 15, 2010 |df= }}</ref><ref>[http://www.llenroc.org/calendar.asp Delta Phi at Cornell&nbsp;-&nbsp;Calendar of Events]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08SB44R?url=http://www.llenroc.org/calendar.asp |date=December 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn or around November 17 of every year, the national organization sponsors the Founder's Day Dinner at the Saint Elmo Club where undergraduates and alumni celebrate the founding of the fraternity.<ref>[http://www.deltaphi.org/events/ Delta Phi Fraternity]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5v08TT9zt?url=http://www.deltaphi.org/events/ |date=December 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Founders==\n* Benjamin Burroughs, [[Presbyterian]] [[Minister of religion|minister]] from [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] \n* William Hun Fondey, [[Lawyer|attorney]] from [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* Samuel Lewis Lamberson, Presbyterian [[Minister of religion|minister]] from [[Jamaica, New York|Jamaica]], New York\n* Samuel C. Lawrison, [[United States Navy]] [[surgery|surgeon]] from [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]], [[Florida]]\n* David Hervey Little, [[New York Supreme Court]] [[Justice]] from [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], New York\n* John Mason, [[clergyman]] from Jamaica, New York\n* Joseph Griffiths Masten, [[Mayor]] of [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] from [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], New York\n* Thomas Clark McLaury, [[clergyman]] from [[Lisbon, New York|Lisbon]], New York\n* William Wilson, [[President (education)|President]] of the College of Cincinnati from [[Ireland]]\n\n==Chapters==\n{{overly detailed|section=yes|date=December 2011}}\n\n===Active chapters===\nThere are 12 active chapters of Delta Phi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Active Chapters - Delta Phi Fraternity|url=http://www.deltaphifraternity.org/?page=AChapters}}</ref> \n* Beta - [[Brown University]], Providence, Rhode Island, 1830-2011<sup>[*]</sup>\n* Epsilon - [[Rutgers University]], New Brunswick, New Jersey, 1845<ref>[http://www.deltaphirutgers.org Epsilon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009090546/http://www.deltaphirutgers.org/ |date=2008-10-09}}</ref>\n* Eta - [[University of Pennsylvania]], Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, 1849<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://stelmopenn.2stayconnected.com/ |title=Eta |access-date=2019-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526225847/https://stelmopenn.2stayconnected.com/ |archive-date=2016-05-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Lambda - [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]], Troy, New York, 1864<ref>[http://deltaphirpi.com/ Lambda]</ref>\n* Xi - [[Johns Hopkins University]], Baltimore, Maryland, 1885\n* Pi - [[Cornell University]], Ithaca, New York, 1891<ref>[http://www.llenroc.org/ Pi]</ref>\n* Rho - [[University of Virginia]], Charlottesville, Virginia, 1908\n* Phi - [[Kenyon College]], Gambier, Ohio, 1940\n* Chi - [[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]], Clinton, New York, 1950<ref>[http://students.hamilton.edu/deltaphi/home/ Chi]</ref>\n* Psi - [[Pennsylvania State University]], State College, Pennsylvania, 1960\u20132007, 2015\n* Omega - [[University of Pittsburgh]], Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, 1968<ref>[https://pittdeltaphi.com Omega]</ref>\n* Omega Alpha - [[College of William and Mary]], Williamsburg, Virginia, 1987<ref>[http://wmdeltaphi.wixsite.com/elmo]</ref>\n\n[*] An active fraternity that is no longer affiliated with the national organization\n\n===Inactive chapters===\nThere are 15 inactive chapters of Delta Phi, including the Alpha Chapter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inactive Chapters - Delta Phi Fraternity|url=http